<p>The song â€œDoom Metalâ€ was first written during that same time I resurrected Wanderlust and Doomsayer, and like those two it was first done on that second Rampage boombox tape (I guess I should do some kind of â€˜session discographyâ€™ so people will know what happened when and allâ€¦ letâ€™s see if anyone cares enough to ask first :) ). The idea came from what was, in my mind, a very funny joke: Venom did â€œBlack Metalâ€. Possessed did â€œDeath Metalâ€. Who did Doom metal? Those two aforementioned songs hit all of the highlights and standard points of their chosen genres, so I thought â€œWhat would such a doom metal song entail?â€ Itâ€™d have to be slow and long, for sure. Lots of Tritone usage. Lyrics about depression and suicide. And the chorus would have to go â€œDooooooomâ€¦.. Metaaaallllâ€¦..â€. Just the whole incongruity of a depressive/introspective song done in the manner of a â€˜big swinging dickâ€™ type of song like Death Metal seemed very funny to me.</p>

<p>I crafted the lyrics and music pretty much at the same time, somewhat in parallel. That clean E-Bb thing was the first part, then modifying it five or six times to get the bulk of riffs for the song. I was always rather proud how I milked that riff for so many versions at the beginning, especially when the double-kick comes in for that 16th-note crunch part. The verses, true to my form at the time, are just over simple 8th-note-open-E, since I was still not that great at singing and playing at the same time.</p>

